"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody. Today I'm going to make a hot compost pile from the beginning where there's nothing here to a big pile of composting stuff. And so I have wood chips over here that I'm going to lay out. I have a 55-gallon bunk drum of vegetable waste from my kitchen. I have a five-gallon drum of vegetable waste from my personal kitchen, not my commercial kitchen. And then I have a bunch of straw or a bunch of hay that's uh uh has a bunch of chicken manure in it that I got from my chicken tractor. And so all these three things are gonna be the heavy nitrogen stuff, and the wood chips are gonna be the heavy carbon stuff. Mix them together, you get that wonderful hot compost for the nitrogen and the carbon bond together, make the best soil known to man. Anyway, let's get started. The first thing we do is create a foundation of wood chips. This is what all of the stinky nitrogen stuff is going to sit on top of. And I have some wood chips and some brush and things like that. And the idea is to completely capture the nitrogen so it does not smell, and so that all of your compost is full of nitrogen because that's the problem. Nitrogen wants to escape. It's a very light gas. Everything is trying to keep the nitrogen in place so that you plants can use it. And so this bonding process is really fundamental because there's not a really good way, other than nitrogen chemical pellets made from a giant factory somewhere to get the nitrogen in there if your soil is hard. Now, if you have soft soil, then atmospheric pressure can do it, and legumes can also do it, and there's lots of good ways. But starting soil off with lots of nitrogen is really the way to go. And so I'm covering all this car or this nitrogen stuff up with heavy carbon, uh, which are the wood chips, and this will lock the nitrogen in. As the nitrogen tries to escape through evaporation, gets such a light gas, it will run into the carbon that's on top. It will bond with the carbon. Uh, the microbes in there are grabbing that nitrogen just as quickly as it moves and bonding it with the carbon. That's what they do. So the idea is to have a really uh is to completely cover all that vegetable refuse and manure with carbon. And here's what you have after. It's a really nice pile, no scent, everything is just beautiful. And this will shrink quite a bit because it's uh very fluffed up, and as that bonding occurs, we'll lose about a third, maybe half of this size. But right now it's just all sitting there, and it's not mixed. In the next couple days, I will come through and pitch it, and that will start the mixing process. But the first thing I do is just set it up. I'm not trying to uh do anything real fancy here, uh, just putting it together and covering it so it doesn't stake. And it doesn't. It's amazing. Anyway, so that's how the pile gets started. Uh hope you enjoyed it, and yeah, there we are. Uh brand new compost pile.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 0.4,\n      \"end\": 1.6,\n      \"duration\": 1.2,\n      \"confidence\": 0.976,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 0.4,\n          \"end\": 0.64,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 0.993\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 0.64,\n          \"end\": 0.8,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 0.88,\n          \"end\": 1.04,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 1.04,\n          \"end\": 1.2,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 1.2,\n          \"end\": 1.36,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\